'''Hydroxyl ion absorption''' is the [[Absorption (optics)|absorption]] in [[optical fiber]]s of [[electromagnetic wave]]s, including the near-[[infrared]], due to the presence of trapped [[hydroxyl]] [[ions]] remaining from water as a contaminant. 

The hydroxyl (OH<sup>‚àí</sup>) ion, can penetrate [[glass]] during or after product fabrication, resulting in significant [[attenuation]] of discrete optical wavelengths, ''e.g.'', centred at 1.383 Œºm, used for [[telecommunication|communications]] via optical fibres.


